SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is a 28 Years old Male presenting for initial allergy evaluation. Patient reports he received his first COVID vaccine (Moderna) on base on 8 Jan 2021. Was in his usual state of health. Waited 15 minutes without adverse reaction. About 35-40 minutes after vaccination while driving home, felt like his tongue was bigger inside his mouth. Patient's wife is a nurse, looked in his mouth, also felt the tongue and uvula were swollen. He did think his airway was compromised. Also had fever about 7 hours after the shot (~100F) resolved with Tylenol. Admits to soreness at injection site and generalized arthralgias for 2 days after injection. Denies associated lightheadedness, syncope, shortness of breath, wheezing, cough, urticaria, conjunctivitis, rhinitis, vomiting, abdominal pain or diarrhea.  Swelling persisted 1.5-2 hours and spontaneously resolved. Did not seek medical attention. Presented to POD for second COVID vaccine dose (due 5 Feb 2021) and was turned away after mentioning his symptoms and was recommended to follow-up with the clinic. He has never experienced swelling before. Vaccines are otherwise up to date; has tolerated all other vaccines. Denies a history of anaphylaxis. Denies adverse reaction to any prior medications. Denies a history of adverse reaction to venom and latex. States gluten sensitive (bloating, diarrhea after ingestion). Denies a history of food allergies. Reports he is allergic to cats and has seasonal allergy symptoms controlled with Benadryl PRN.  Denies a history of adverse reaction to polyethylene glycol (PEG), a polysorbate, or polyoxyl 35 castor oil containing injectable or vaccine. Takes an OTC stool softener PRN containing docusate and sennosides.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin C; Benadryl PRN; OTC Docusate/Sennosides

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About a week after my vaccine I began feeling some swelling at the intersection of my left armpit. Next day was some more so but didn't hurt, just swollen feeling. I figured it was from the shot since I'd recently had a mammogram and it was clear. A few days later I figured I should put it on my vsafe checking, but apparently it had expired. Today I  read an article that said some women had felt a lump under their arm after getting the COVID-19 shot and gone to the doctor, gotten a mammogram, and swelling showed on the picture.  Final statement of the article said it is most likely a reaction of the lymph node (mine was same side as shot[left] except one day only on right side) to the injection. Not to be concerned unless it lasted over a month, then see your doctor. I thought it might be helpful for both of us if I reported this. I'll keep track and see Dr. Last if it lasts more than a month.

The patient stated that she did not realize, but she must have been exposed to the COVID Virus, prior to getting her shot. She stated that on 15Jan2021, she went and got her Pfizer COVID shot, and that same day, by the time she got home, she was starting to feel bad and it went downhill from there. She mentioned that on the same day on 15Jan2021, she "came down with covid". She finally went in on 22Jan2021, and got tested, and she did test positive for COVID. The patient was tested Positive for COVID-19 on 22Jan2021. She did believe she was getting better. On 29Jan2021, she felt fairly decent, and today, she is kind of weak but she is assuming that will happen. She was scheduled to go back for her second dose on 08Feb2021, and she is wondering if there are recommendations about the second dose, for people who tested positive for COVID after having gotten the first dose. When queried for her PCP contact information, she stated that her head is not working really great and she feels stupid she did not have this information handy to provide. She states that the first week with her symptoms, she just figured she did have the virus. She had a cough but it never got down to where she had trouble breathing, and she just figured that her body had to go through, whatever it was going to go through, and as long as the patient felt like she was okay, there was not anything anyone could do, she just had to play it out. When she did finally go get tested, the doctor told her to get on Nyquil and Ibuprofen, so that is what the patient has been taking, and she feels like it has helped a lot. Before she saw the doctor, she was taking Acetaminophen, but the doctor told her to do the Nyquil and Ibuprofen, so that is what she has been doing. By the time she got home from getting her vaccine, her heart was racing. She took her blood pressure and it was okay at 125/73, and her heart rate was 72. She has high blood pressure and she takes two medications for that, so she took her night time blood pressure pill and the fast beating of her heart went away. The next day, she got to aching. She has had all different aches, and she ran a fever that got up to 101, and the rest of the time it was 100 or 99, but the fevers were not all day long, they would just come and go. Now she has had no fever in four or more days, and she is doing better. She does still have the cough, but she also has allergies so she does not know what is causing the cough. As far as the reaction to the vaccine, just her arm got sore. But she thinks she was exposed prior to getting the vaccine and just did not know it. she stated that the people took her temperature the day of the shot and she didn't have a temperature. She did not receive any other vaccines on the same day as the COVID vaccine. The outcome of fever was recovering, of cough and allergies was not recovered, of her heart was racing was recovered.

Vomiting; Nausea; Spontaneous report received on 14FEB2020.  A caregiver (consumer's mother) reported that her 23-year-old daughter had nausea (PT: Nausea) and vomiting (PT: Vomiting) while being on Vivotif for immunisation. On 07FEB2020, the consumer took first dose of Vivotif and felt nauseated on the same day. On 13FEB2020 at approximately 05:00 pm, she took the last dose of Vivotif and vomited at 11:00 pm approximately. Moreover, she had not vomited again. Action taken with Vivotif with respect to the reported event nausea was dose not changed while, with respect to the event vomiting was not applicable. She had recovered from the event vomiting while the outcome of the event nausea was unknown.  Past medications included meningitis vaccine (meningococcal vaccine), polio vaccine and yellow fever vaccine, which were received on 21JAN2020.  She was concomitantly taking medication for birth control.  Company Comment: A consumer felt nauseated (nausea) after taking first dose of Vivotif, and then she had vomiting within a few hours of taking last dose of Vivotif. Vomiting was resolved and the outcome of nausea was unknown. Considering the events occurred after taking Vivotif and the potential of Vivotif to cause both these events, the causality of nausea and vomiting is assessed as possible with Vivotif.; Sender's Comments: A consumer felt nauseated (nausea) after taking first dose of Vivotif, and then she had vomiting within a few hours of taking last dose of Vivotif. Vomiting was resolved and the outcome of nausea was unknown. Considering the events occurred after taking Vivotif and the potential of Vivotif to cause both these events, the causality of nausea and vomiting is assessed as possible with Vivotif.

On 13 Feb 2021 at 3:30 pm, the patient could not be woken up and was found with no pulse or heartbeat.   Action taken with the drug in response to the events was not applicable.  The outcome of the events, no pulse or heartbeat and couldn't wake him up, were not provided. The patient died on 13 Feb 2021. The cause of death was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Very limited information regarding this event/s has been provided at this time. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Belligerent; scatter-brained; Erratic; Delusional; A spontaneous report was received on 16FEB2021 from a caregiver concerning a 91-years-old, male patient who received second dose of Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine and became belligerent, delusional, erratic and scatter-brained.  The patient's medical history, as reported by the consumer, include Myasthenia gravis (MG). Relevant concomitant medications reported included prednisone 10 mg, nortriptyline HCL 10 mg caps QD, tamsulosin HCL 0.4 mg caps BID, lisinopril 5 mg QD, gabapentin 200 mg QD night, pyridostigmine 90 mg TID, xanax 25 mg as needed, lexapro 5mg QD, levothyroxine 50 mcg QD, amiodarone HCL 200mg QD, carvedilol 6.25 mg BID. He had been on prednisone 20 mg for 6 weeks and they dropped it to 10mg a week before he received his first vaccine. Patient was taking prednisone for Myasthenia Gravis.  On 06JAN2021, patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273(BATCH/LOT # 012L20A) injection intramuscularly for the prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On 09FEB2021, patient received their second of two planned doses of mRNA-1273(BATCH/LOT # 007M208) intramuscularly for the prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  After receiving second dose of vaccine, patient became belligerent, erratic and scatter-brained. He has no history of dementia.   On 16FEB2021 at 3:30am, patient called 911 for a foot fungus and paramedics took him to the hospital. The caregiver stated that he was delusional. Treatment for the events were not provided.  The outcome of the events, belligerent, delusional, erratic and scatter-brained, were unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Red streak on inner side of left arm; Felt was going to die; General malaise; Weakness; Slight dizziness; Nausea; Vomited; Blood pressure fluctuation; Hives on inner arms; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer and physician concerning a 83-year-old, female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced felt was going to die, general malaise, red streak on inner side of left arm, hives on inner arms, weakness, dizziness, blood pressure fluctuating, nausea and vomited.   The patient's medical history included breast cancer, breast cancer surgery and hives. Concomitant product use was not provided.   On 05 Jan 2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (lot #: 039K20A) (route of administration not specified) in the right arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   On 17 Jan 2021, 12 to 13 days after the vaccination, the patient developed hives on inner arms which would come and go, appearing in the morning and disappearing during daytime. Patient took Benadryl for it and applied cortisone cream.  On 26 Jan 2021, after taking a walk, the patient experienced weakness, slight dizziness, and nausea. Patient was taken to the emergency room (ER) and vomited. The patient was sent home the same day but the patient's blood pressure was noted to be fluctuating.  On 27 Jan 2021, the patient "felt that she was going to die" and had general malaise. The patient was brought to the ER of another hospital but again was sent home.  On 29 Jan 2021, with the symptoms still ongoing and a red streak noted on the inner side of the left arm, the patient was admitted for observation at the second hospital.  Laboratory details included Blood works and radiologic tests were done with normal results. The patient's blood pressure was stabilized but patient was still experiencing malaise and still had the on and off rash on both inner arms.    Treatment information included Benadryl and Cortisone Cream for the indication hives.   Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was not reported.  The event, blood pressure fluctuation, was considered resolved/recovered on 01 Feb 2021.  The outcome of the events, hives on inner arms, red streak on inner side of left arm, weakness, dizziness, nausea, vomited, felt was going to die and general malaise, was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Further information has been requested.  This case concerns an 83-year-old female hospitalized with serious unexpected malaise, erythema, anxiety, and NS unexpected urticaria, asthenia, dizziness, BP fluctuation and NS expected nausea, vomiting. Event onset 23 days after the first dose of mRNA-1273. BP changes resolved, other events unknown. As above, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Breast cancer; Hives (History of hives three times previously in her life.); Surgery (Breast cancer surgery.)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Bell's Palsy; Neck pain and rigidity; Neck pain and rigidity; Pain in the ear; Epiphora; Could not blink; Shoulder soreness; Chills; Fever; A spontaneous report was received from a Consumer and a healthcare professional concerning a � 35 Years-old female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced facial paralysis, arthralgia, chills, fever, neck pain, nuchal rigidity, ear pain, lacrimation increased and lagophthalmos.  The patient's medical history was not provided. No relevant concomitant medications were reported.    On 12-Feb-2021, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their second planned dose of mRNA-1273 (lot/batch: 030M20A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On the same day, the patient experienced shoulder soreness, pain in the ear, chills, fever, neck pain and rigidity, epiphora, couldn't blink and face paralysis. Our Covid vaccination clinic screens patients for qualifying and disqualifying factors, including age, immediately before they receive a vaccination. Screeners are responsible for this. This event occurred because a mistake was made during the screening process.

i had tetanus boosters in 1975 and 1984, and again once after that of a date unrecalled.  each time i had sever arm pain and was unable to move arm for about a week.  not once was i told that would be a contraindication to further vaccination. in 1990, as a checker at a market, after 3 months i acquired a repetitive strain injury.  it occurred unusually quickly and did not resolve with normal treatment.  i have now been receiving treatment for 30 years, and still impacts me.  I did not realize until recently that the etiology of the injury was from brachial neuritis due to the tetanus shot.  all providers who have treated me said my injury was unusual lu extreme considering the supposed onset.   i have complex involvement of the fascia, and could not work for years.  i need constant graston treatment to break up the scarring.  it mimics chronic tetanus and i am saddened that doctors did not recognize the syndrome sooner.
PRIOR_VAX: cannot recall, developed asthma, excema, and ulcerative colitis after boosters

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 3-inch area of skin that turned bright red; the area was like a hot rash but no itching; the area being hot to the touch; the area feeling like rocks under the skin; Initial information was received on 16-Feb-2021 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case was received from a Consumer or Non-healthcare professional via Medical Information (Reference number- 00478096) and transmitted to Sanofi on 16-Feb-2021.  This case involves a 82-year-old female patient who experienced 3-inch area of skin that turned bright red (vaccination site erythema), the area was like a hot rash but no itching (vaccination site rash), the area being hot to the touch (vaccination site warmth) and the area feeling like rocks under the skin (vaccination site induration), while she received vaccine INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE [FLUZONE HIGH-DOSE QUADRIVALENT].  Medical history, medical treatment(s), concomitant medications and family history were not provided. The patient's past vaccination(s) included FLUARIX.  On 16-Oct-2020, the patient received 0.7 mL dose (total) of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE [lot number not reported and expiry date not provided] via intramuscular route in left arm for prophylactic vaccination.  On 16-Oct-2020, the patient developed non-serious 3-inch area of skin that turned bright red (vaccination site erythema), the area was like a hot rash but no itching (vaccination site rash), the area being hot to the touch (vaccination site warmth) and the area feeling like rocks under the skin (vaccination site induration), on the same day following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE.  Details of laboratory data were not reported.  The daughter reported that for the first 72-hours after the vaccine administration, was the worst, then the area on the 6th day began going down, that the color had changed back to normal within a week, that the consumer did apply an ice pack to the area, that the ice pack was not felt due to the area being hot, that Arnica cream was applied and it helped; that the prescriber does not feel it was an allergic reaction, that another patient in the clinic reported the same injection site reaction to the FLUZONE Quadrivalent High Dose this year.  On an unknown date, patient had recovered from the events.  The consumer had almost the same reaction with other flu vaccines in the past, that the consumer had reactions for most flu vaccines but the usual reaction is not as visible as the most recent, that she had the reaction with Fluarix, that the consumer is scheduled to get the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. and that there have been reports of people getting the Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine having reactions on the arm.The daughter wanting to know would a reaction to the Fluzone Quadrivalent High Dose mean a similar reaction with the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine.  There will be no information available on batch number for this case.

Approximately 60 hours after my second injection I was awoken from my sleep with the most intense, excruciating pain in my right arm (arm where the vaccine was injected), It felt like every muscle was being torn off. I had been laying on my back at the time and the pain did not go away by repositioning my arm. The pain would eventually radiate all the way down to my right hand and my ring and pinky fingers experienced numbness as did my right hand which also felt colder than my left hand. The pain also ran up to my shoulder around to my scapula, under my arm and up my neck. The pain still exists today 18 days post vaccine. I have been taking ibuprofen and Tylenol around the clock to alleviate the pain. I also was given a steroid dose pack by my neurologist. Sometimes the pain subsides but it always comes back. Sometimes I still feel like I have been punched in the arm where the injection occurred and other times it is my scapula that is so tender I cannot lay on my back. I have to sleep on my back at night and if I try to roll over on my left side, the side where I was not injected, my right arm feels tingly.
LAB_DATA: I had a vitural dr appointment with my neurologist on 2/22/2021. She explained she had a similar reaction to the vaccine that eventually subsided. She perscribed the steroid dose pack which really did not help. I saw an orthopedic dr. on 3/1/2021. He examined me and took x-rays and did not find anything wrong with my shoulder. He thinks I may be suffering from a pinched nerve. Maybe the injection was administered incorrectly? I am not ruling this out or the possibility that this is indeed an adverse reaction to the vaccine itself.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Headaches everyday

In the first 12-18 hours I felt the expected soreness at the injection site. I also experienced a mild fever (no higher than 99.5) in the first 24 hours.   Between 18 and 24 hours post-injection I started to feel neuralgia through my entire arm, with shooting pains from my shoulder to my palm. My palm and heel of my hand felt tingly, numb, burning, or cold at various points. The pain in my arm was subjectively a 6-8 on the average 10-point rating scale, with constant pain accompanied by shooting pains, hot and cold sensations, tingling, and numbness. The most severe pains caused nausea. While these symptoms mostly subsided after about 72 hours post-injection, I still have fleeting sensations of cold and numbness from below my elbow to the heel of my hand.   I used Voltaren gel, a heating pad, Icy Hot, hot showers, supportive pillows and massage to manage the symptoms. I took Tylenol, Skelexin, and zolpidem tartrate to help alleviate the worst of the pain and allow for sleep. I considered seeking care at an urgent care center, but was not willing to risk COVID exposure in a medical facility.

On my exam, she had "Confluent red, non blanching on lower legs (ie, more purpuric), blanching and confluent on inner thighs and anterior thighs.  More papular-confluent on R arm.  Min on abd, spares back and posterior thighs, palms and face.  Oropharynx and conj are ok" (Derm felt lesions were more urticarial than macular papular). She had some cough, chest tightness.  On the following day, when we walked her, her RA O2 satn dropped to mid 80s% then up to RA satn 93%.  She also had joint pains, particularly in hands. She was started on 70 mg of prednisone on 2/25--and improved thereafter.   By 2/28, her RA satn at rest was 98%, but dropped to 94% with walking.   The rash, skin discomfort and chest tightness improved.  Even her clients now say, she no longer sounds "like a dead horsse"  (she told me this on phone when I asked her vaccine details and told her I was reporting). Respiratory:  Lungs are clear to auscultation, respirations are non-labored, breath sounds are equal,  no retractions.   Gastrointestinal:  Soft, Nontender, Non distended. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I arrived and was let into a tent, I sat down and the nurse (no name tag) asked which arm. I pulled up my sleeve and I relaxed my arm and she stuck the needle in my arm and nurse proclaimed "uh-oh, the syringe didn't work and the needle didn't pop in. That has never happened before. Let me find out what to do." Very little if any of the vaccine in the syringe went into the arm. I saw other syringes on a table nearby and the syringe use on me had the same amount as the vials on the table. She left the tent and came back a few minutes later and said "someone is checking with the pharmacy to see what we can do. Please wait in the observation area." I got up and went to the observation area. After about 10 minutes another employee and the nurse walked up to me (no name tags) and they said " so, the FDA does not allow us to administer partial doses." I said  "Ok, I didnt receive the dose though..." Nurse looked at her phone and was looking at text messages ( I could see because I was standing and she was sitting.) and then she said the exact same thing to me again. I said "Are you going to give me the second dose, or not?" the nurse saind " Probably not. Its been 15 minutes, so  you can leave." So I left and drove 2 hours home. My daughter found on the CDC website an article "Interim Clinical Consideration for use of MRNA Covid 19 Vaccines Currently Authorized"  from Feb 10th 2021 under Dosage it says "if lower than dose required is administered, or patient pulls back, or it leaked out, or there is a needle/syringe malfunction, if less than half the dose was administered, administer the authorized dose immediately  in the opposite arm."

Patient also states she is had some occasional dizziness which she described as a room spinning sensation is made worse when she is in positions and standing or moves her head.  She has a history of 2 heart attacks and 2 stents placed which were done.  She has no local cardiology follow-up and she lives at an apartment and follows with pace.  EMS gave her 4 aspirin prior to arrival she takes no blood thinners but she does take Plavix.  Patient has a history of COPD and also endorses some wheezing, she says they took her nebulizer away from her for fear of spreading coronavirus and she is oxygen dependent at nighttime. Start IV Solu-Medrol  COVID-19 viral infection: Start IV Remdesivir as she is now requiring supplemental oxygen.  IV steroids as above. Continue to trend troponin x2 more occurrences. --Continue Aspirin, Plavix, statin, Imdur.   Anxiety disorder: Continue Prozac. SYMPTOM_TEXT: passed out; almost delirious; couldn't lift leg; pain went all the way down left side of body; sweating; chills; felt heavy weight on chest; left leg hurting so bad like a charley horse; weak all over; allergic reaction; pain in left arm at injection site; felt extremely tired; A spontaneous report was received from a consumer, via notification from another manufacturer, concerning a 79 year-old female patient who experienced an allergic reaction (hypersensitivity); passed out (loss of consciousness); almost delirious (delirium); couldn't lift leg (femoral nerve injury); pain radiating down leg (pain); sweating (hyperhidrosis); chills; heavy weight on chest (chest discomfort); leg hurting like Charlie horse (muscle spasms); weak all over (asthenia); pain in left arm where she got the shot (injection site pain); felt extremely tired (fatigue).    The patient's medical history included sinus issues and drug allergies to glycopyrrolate, sulfa, meloxicam, erythromycin and azithromycin.  The patient stated that she had a long list of names and ingredients of things she is allergic to.  Products known to have been used by the patient, within two weeks prior to the event, included Amiodipine.    On 28 Jan 2021, approximately 12 hours prior to the onset of the symptoms, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Batch number: 028120A) intramuscularly in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.   The patient reported that she received the vaccine dose around 12:00 or 12:30 pm.  The patient reported that she woke up with extreme pain in the left side and in the left arm where she got the shot.  The pain went all the way down her body and she reported it as severe pain.  She reported that the pain would not go away.  The patient reported that she started sweating, had chills, and she felt heavy like a weight on her chest, but she was breathing okay.  Her leg on the left side started hurting so bad that it was like a big Charley horse that would not go away.   She got out of the bed and tried to see if she could stand on it, but she could not.  She tried to rub it, but it did not help.  She tried to walk on it, but by that time she was almost delirious.  She was sweating so bad and she was weak all over.  She had become extremely tired and she ended up laying on the floor because she could not get her leg to lift in order to get back in the bed so she just laid on the floor.  By that point, she did not know if she had passed out or fallen asleep, but she does not think she fell asleep because it was too much pain to sleep.  When she woke up and came to, the pain in her leg was gone.  However, she was still sweating.  She could not get back in the bed.  The following morning, she was extremely weak and tired.  She still felt heavy on her chest like something had been pushed on her.  She was hurting, weak, and tired, but the pain was not extreme like it had been that night.  She clarified the time of onset for this event was around midnight, but she could not look at the clock to confirm the exact time.  She reported the event either started the night of 28 Jan 2021 or early in the morning hours of 29 Jan 2021.  She called her doctor, Moderna, and the pharmacist to ask about the ingredients of the vaccine.  Treatment information was unknown.   Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events  was withdrawn.  The events, passed out and pain in left leg, was considered resolved the following day.  The events of sweating, weakness, tiredness, and heavy chest was improved the following day.  The outcome of the events, allergic reaction, delirious, pain in left arm, pain in left side of body, chills, couldn't lift leg, was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the event, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Patient received both scheduled doses of mRNA-1273 prior to the events; therefore, action taken with the drug in response to the events are not applicable. Patient reports that previous to vaccination her blood pressure had been running in the normal range 120's/70's the majority of the time on lisinopril-hydrochlorothiazide 20-25 mg daily alone. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Second dose of Pfizer vaccine was given 1/10/2021 around 9:30 AM. I woke up at around 6:30 AM on 1/13/2021 feeling well.  While I was changing, I noticed a diffuse maculopapular rash on my torso back thighs and upper arms.  The rash was very pruritic.  I took some Benadryl which did not seem to help the itchiness and made me sleepy.  By Thursday, most of the rash on the torso was gone, but the rash had spread more to my forearms, lower legs, feet and hands.  There was some mild edema of the hands, I had some mild fatigue, and temperature check was slightly elevated around 99 degrees F.   By Friday, most of the rash was gone and I had some remaining itchiness of feet and hands.  Saturday I was back to normal.

I am a 75 year old female with severe Cardiomyopathy with an ejection fraction of less than 20% and an implanted defibrillator. I had my first COVID vaccine on Sunday, February 28.  I had had sinus problems with a little runny nose the week before...no fever, no chills, normal temperature.  Other than my arm being a little sore, i took two Tylenol the night of the vaccine and had no problems until Tuesday afternoon, March 2, 2021. i felt perfectly Sunday after =noon, all day Monday and Tuesday.  However while shopping at a nearby store as I got to the checkout counter I started having shortness of breath, It was hard for me to walk and I was very shaky.  I have an apple watch so I was able to check my heart rate.  The heart rate was anywhere from 58BPM to 177BPM and all over place in between,  i got in my car, trying to calm myself then called the EMTs.  They took me to hospital to the Emergency Room.  Several tests(see below) were performed.  The final diagnosis was hear palpitations.  They did a COVID test and I did test positive for the Rhino virus.  The doctors didn't know if my incident was related to receive the COVID vaccine and my defibrillator was checked, and a test was run that indicated it wasn't bad enough to activate the defibrillator.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Developed Shingles 2 days after vaccine

Client received the vaccine and was sitting for her 15 minute observation period. About 10 minutes into her observation period, client stated she felt dizzy and her neck hurt. RN got an icepack to her neck and was about to get client's jacket off and client fainted. Client was guided to the ground, RN did a sternal rub and after about 15 seconds after initial loss of consciousness, client regained consciousness. Client stated she felt like she was going to vomit and client was turned on her side. Client then stated her lips were numb but denied any SOB. She remained alert and orientated and continued to deny SOB. EMS arrived, client was given fluids, Benadryl, Pepcid, and solumedrol. Client was stable and transported to ER via ambulance
LAB_DATA: Per client due to high BP, client had "heart tests" but all tests were normal. Client is to continue to check BP twice daily and has a scheduled appointment with her primary provider for follow up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: A first dose MODERNA was administered to the 13 year old by a nursing student. A local Health Department has partnered with another company to have a COVID vaccine clinic where the instructors are supervising nursing students administering vaccine. A student inadvertently gave the 13 year old who presented with parents who also received the vaccine. My wife had IPF and passed away. We have an Oximeter Plus here at home. I began to feel extremely tired and decided to check my O2 sat. I was roughly 2 hours following my shot. My O2 sat is normally 97-98. When I checked it it had dropped to 84. This is abnormal for me. It remained at this level until about 4 hours after my shot when I checked it had returned to my normal level. This does give m some concern about my follow up vaccine.

Chest tightness; Difficulty breathing; Voice is hoarse, voice changes; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of chest tightness in a 54-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 2nd February 2021, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 2nd February 2020, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced chest tightness, difficulty breathing and voice alteration. On an unknown date, the outcome of the chest tightness was unknown and the outcome of the difficulty breathing and voice alteration were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the chest tightness, difficulty breathing and voice alteration to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows:  After receiving 1st dose of Shingrix, the patient experienced chest tightness, difficulty breathing, and his voice is hoarse, voice changes. The patient reported that he did not want to provide his health care provider's information. The reporter did not consent to follow up.

Fetal exposure during pregnancy; Birth weight of 4366 g; This observational study case, initially received on 23-Feb-2021 from other health professional and concerned a female neonate patient, whose mother was 31-year-old, pregnant subject of body weight 174 lbs, height 62 inches and body mass index (BMI) 31.8; enrolled in, a prospective observational safety study.  The maternal medical history included high BMI, nausea and vomiting. The maternal concomitant medications included Prenatal vitamins (unspecified minerals and vitamins) for pregnancy and ondansetron for nausea and vomiting.  The neonate's mother's obstetrical history included one previous pregnancy with spontaneous abortion. The neonate's mother had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM) and no maternal and paternal history with MCM. The neonate's mother did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The neonate's mother's last menstrual period (LMP) was reported as 11-Oct-2019. The mother's estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 17-Jul-2020 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was not reported. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 09-Dec-2019, the ultrasound revealed no MCM.   On 06-Jan-2020, at approximately 12 weeks of gestation (calculated pet LMP), the neonate's mother was administered Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL) [influenza vaccine; dose, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported] (explicitly coded as 'Foetal exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation. Batch number reported was  P100112488.   On 03-Feb-2020, the gender ultrasound scan revealed no MCM.  At gestational age of 41 week (as reported), the mother vaginally delivered live female neonate. The neonate's birth weight was 4366 grams, head circumference and body length were not reported. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) score at one minute, at five minutes and at 10 minutes were not provided. There was no MCM noted at birth.   The outcome of the event 'high birthweight baby' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide causality assessment.  The event of 'high birthweight baby' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  This case is linked with case 202003732, due to corresponding mother case.  Company comment: A female neonate was exposed to the suspect product, Afluria QIV. The neonate's mother was vaccinated with Afluria QIV at gestational age of 12 weeks. Neonate's weight on birth was 4366 grams. Causality between suspect product and event of large for dates baby is assessed as not related due to biological implausibility. Per some sources, the range of normal is between 2.5 and 4.5 kilograms. Foetal exposure during pregnancy is assessed as not related per company's conventions.; Sender's Comments: A female neonate was exposed to the suspect product, Afluria QIV. LAB_DATA: Flexible sigmoidoscopy performed at hospital 2/12/21: Parts of the distal transverse, descending and sigmoid colon were visualized. Patient was at clinic to receive his 2nd dose of the Moderna CoVID-19 Vaccine.  Approx 13 minutes after receiving the dose, patient became weak, dizzy, and extremely diaphoretic.  Rapid response was called.  Patient was wheeled into exam room.  BG checked immediately and was 110.  Initial vitals showed HR 39 with BP 83/48.  Patient was transferred to exam table w/o incident.  He did not complain of CP or SOB.  Denies any throat swelling or itching.  He felt very weak and tired.  He continued to be extremely diaphoretic.  An 18G IV was introduced to the left forearm without incident.  He was connected to 1 L bag of 0.9% Normal Saline which was hung to bolus, running well without pressure.  EKG obtained and showed sinus bradycardia with a rate of 43.  Possible ST changes in V1 and V2, but not diagnostic of ST elevations or depressions.  There is IVCD noted.  Patient has hx of AFib - not in Afib currently.  Reports on Eliquis instead of Coumadin.  EMS was contacted.    Physical exam performed revealed a bradycardic HR which was regular. No murmurs.  Lungs are clear.  Patient is extremely diaphoretic and pale.  He is alert and oriented x 3.  He is not in respiratory distress and shows no signs of oral swelling. No hives noted on his skin.  Vitals were rechecked at 3 mins and showed SaO2 at 95% and then 92%.  NC O2 applied at 2 L/min continuous and there was improvement to 95%.  He still denies any respiratory distress and was not manifesting any signs of respiratory distress.  Still denied any chest pain.  NS continued to infuse at bolus dose and BP recheck improved to 108/65 - patient was lying supine.  HR remained between 40-42.  At this time, the patient reported improved symptoms and he was not sweating as profusely as previously.  At this time EMS arrived.  Atropine was not administered in the clinic, but was prepared in expectation as a possible next step.  As patient's symptoms improved, but his vital signs remained altered, he was agreeable to transport to the hospital by EMS.  He was placed on stretcher and care was relinquished to EMS team.  Patient transported out of clinic in guarded condition.
LAB_DATA: EKG, IV insertion, 1 L Normal Saline

Per telephone encounter on 2/26/21: Mother verbalizes that patient received 2-month vaccines on Tuesday 2/23/21. Injection sites were slightly red, and patient had a low-grade temperature, so they gave patient Infant Tylenol. Patient was okay afterwards and injection sites were no longer red. However, last night 2/25/21 mother noticed small red bumps on bilateral legs. This morning 2/26/21 the small red bumps are now also on bilateral arms and some on her neck. Mother is wondering if this is related to the vaccines or if it could be related to the Vitamin D drops, they also started on Tuesday 2/23/21. Afebrile. No other symptoms currently. Bumps do not seem to bother patient. Eating and sleeping normal. Denies drainage. Same day appointment scheduled with Dr. on 2/26/21. Dr.'s note after appointment on 2/26/21: 1. Rash and nonspecific skin eruption; Clinical Notes: 7-week-old infant presents to the office for follow-up evaluation of generalized rash which started 48 hours after her vaccine administration. Rash started as a few erythematous lesions and became generalized over the last 24 hours. She is eating well and does not have any vomiting or diarrhea. She has no URI symptoms cough or congestion. She has no fever. She appears well on today's exam. The appearance of rash after 48 hours of vaccination is concerning for a delayed hypersensitivity reaction but unlikely to be IgE mediated response. I would like to obtain consultation with allergy immunology regarding the etiology of the rash. The only booster that she has received is hepatitis B, other vaccines have been given for the first time on 2/23/2021. I will plan to report the rash to VAERS and also seek consultation from National advisory committee web portal via electronic communication. This will help us to figure out if the next set of vaccinations can be given safely. Referral sent To: Allergy/Immunology: Reason:7-week-old infant has generalized erythematous maculopapular rash almost like urticarial vasculitis. Please evaluate for allergic/drug reaction due to vaccination. Dr.'s note after appointment on 3/2/21: Clinical Notes: Patient recently had urticaria for 2 days, occurring 2 days after routine childhood vaccines. She was also feeding on milk-based formula, but the hives seemed to resolve after changing from milk (and also avoiding soy). Mother has a lot of soy in her diet. Still receiving some breast milk also. The reaction was unlikely due to any of the vaccines, and even if the vaccines were related, there were no symptoms to suggest an immediate anaphylactic reaction. Any vaccine can also cause some local swelling or rashes or low-grade fevers due to the normal immune response. Recommend continued vaccination according to the ACIP schedule. SPT for milk was positive and negative for soy, giving some evidence that the hives were due to cow's milk. Recommended to her mother continued avoidance of cow's milk and dairy, including in the mother's diet while still breastfeeding. Also discussed the signs/symptoms of anaphylaxis. Should this occur, use an Auvi-Q and go to the ER. If symptoms persist in 10-15 minutes, then use the second one. Carry 2 at all times. Proper use of Auvi-Q taught and also provided information for milk avoidance and referred to the website. Will f/u in 1 year to repeat SPT for milk. Call or f/u sooner PRN.

I repeatedly addressed patient by his first name and asked if he could hear me and repeatedly asked if he was okay. Patient began slumping down in his chair but was still conscious. Patient was not responsive but made eye contact with me. Patient requested water. After giving patient water and observing him drink he began looking nauseous and threw up. Patient then passed out in his chair. I supported the patient upright in his chair and made sure he did not fall down or injure his head. I then immediately tapped him on both shoulders and repeatedly called his name. Patient then became responsive and 911 was called. While waiting patient said he was starting to feel better and was able to support himself in his chair. I did not observe any injuries due to fainting. When the ambulance came patient agreed to be taken to the hospital.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: March 3, 2021 SUBJECT: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine, Side Effects This letter/email is addressed to a number of individuals with a request that you seriously evaluate the below discussion, take action to alert medical staff of your respective agencies of these side effects, and work with the manufacturer, Moderna, to address them.  As the recipient of them it has thus far been debilitating and interfered with my daily activities.  It is my hope that the medical community can find ways to prevent or treat them such that daily activity can be unimpeded.     I will first provide a chronology of my medical history and my Moderna vaccine experience.  Then I will discuss my observations. My medical history: Age: 78 Gender: Male Pre-existing Conditions: Medications  Hypertension: Blood pressure medication, 50 mg of Metoprolol Succinate ER daily  Cholesterol: Atorvastatin, 40 mg daily Medical History   2018: Triple By-Pass Surgery 2019: Passed out, Hit head on falling, Brain bleed: Subdural Hematoma, Hospitalized: No surgery required and released.  Subsequently, pacemaker installed. 2021: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine administered.  First Dose: Lot Number: 011J20A, Date: 01/08/2021, Clinic Site: Pharmacy  Second Dose: Lot Number: 032L20A, Date: 02/05/2021, Clinic Site: Pharmacy  Side Effects to Moderna Vaccine administration  First Dose: Administration Site: Swelling, Site Redness and Fever.  All dissipated within week after administration  Second Dose: Fever and Chills day following administration.  Lethargic for several days following administration.  These symptoms disappeared. Observations  February 24, 2021: Began to experience dizziness, symptoms progressed to mild vertigo.  Based on history of presentation of these symptoms, assumed I had an inter-ear problem and began taking Zyrtec D, half a tablet.  Experience with Zyrtec D has been that ear dries out and symptoms of dizziness and disorientation disappear.  In this case the symptoms of vertigo progressed to the point of difficulty in walking and loss of balance. Stopped taking Zyrtec D on Friday, February 26th.  February 26, 2021: Had more severe vomiting, walking difficulty and lose of balance.  Used walker to stabilize walking.  At approximately 7 to 7:30 PM, following consultation with wife and daughter, decided to go the emergency room of the Medical Center (MC).  Was quickly seen by emergency room staff.  Following questions on medical history, the ER doctor, based on head bleed history, I believe, had a CT conducted.  I do not recall any questions about COVID-19, but do think we told them that both myself and my wife had been vaccinated for COVID-19.  I specifically recall that prior to my transport, a nurse came in to do a nasal swab for COVID-19.  I informed her that I had been vaccinated, but she said this was a requirement for admission to the location where I was being transported.  Following the CT scan, the ER physician determined he believed there was a possibility of a small new brain bleed.  At approximately 2 to 2:30 AM I was transported by ambulance to Health Center at approximately 5:00 AM.  I am not certain about the exact times here.  February 27, 2021: Health Center administered a number of tests including CT scan, EKG, and an echocardiogram.  While there, physical therapists came to see me twice and exercised me to improve my balance and walking ability.  The last one recommended exercises to help reset my vestibular system.  Based on the administered CT scan there, the physicians saw no evidence of a new brain bleed and were prepared to release me.  At the time of that discussion in my room, the attending nurse pointed out to the physician there that my blood pressure was elevated.  He ordered a new EKG and deferred on releasing me until a cardiologist reviewed the results.  Their concern was that I was experiencing episodes of atrial fibrillation (AFib).  Subsequently, the cardiologist reviewed the new EKG and concluded the episodes were within the normal range, my understanding, but did note that my heart rate was elevated.  At no time did the medical staff raise or question the possibility of COVID-19 side effects as being a possible explanation for my disorientation or heart rate problem.  I was released later that day.  February 28, 2021:  While speaking to her sister, my wife shared with her my experience of dizziness and disorientation.  Her sister related that her husband had and was experiencing a similar event.  Further, her husband?s sister had experienced a similar event.  Additionally, the husband?s sister had experienced vertigo.  On further discussion it was determined all three of us had received the Moderna Vaccine, and approximately three to four weeks post second dose administration, developed these symptoms of vertigo.  This prompted me to go to the internet for information on vaccine side effects.  The Food and Drug Administration Fact Sheet, revised 12/2020 in the Section Titled: What are the risks of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine? speaks of severe allergic reactions including: a fast heartbeat and dizziness and weakness.  I believe that I have suffered these two reactions.  March 1, 2021:  Called both hospitals to alert them to inform their respective staffs of the need to question the possibility of these side effects should other patients present in their emergency rooms.  In my case, it may have helped to alleviate my concerns had I been informed of these possible side effects.  At MC I left a voice mail for the Chief Medical Officer and at Health Center I spoke to the Nursing Supervisor.  The nursing supervisor advised me to report my side effects and directed me to call the entity who had administered the vaccine doses.  I called the Pharmacist and spoke to her.  She said she would report my concerns through her reporting system.  Further she informed me that there was a medication my primary care provider could prescribe.  I called my primary care provider, and he has prescribed Meclizine, 25 mg tablets.  I am currently taking � tablet, three times per day.  A whole tablet made me drowsy.  As of today, March 3, 2021, I am still experiencing disorientation.  Hopefully this will subside and disappear. The above discussion is provided to assist medical professionals to further assess the side effects of the Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine.  I am glad that I received it.  I have no complaint about the care I received at the two medical facilities referenced.  In fact, I think it was excellent.  However, it would have helped me to have raised by either or both of them that my symptoms may have been COVID-19 Vaccine related.  Further, it may have changed how they proceeded in assessing my situation. As an industrial hygienist with statistical training, it seems to me somewhat unusual to have three members of my extended family experiencing similar dizziness and weakness side effects, and for us all to have similar time periods following the administration of the second dose.  Perhaps, if related to the vaccine, this cluster would suggest that this side effect may be more common than a ?remote chance.?  Should any of you have further questions or wish to speak to me, please do not hesitate to call.  Since I get a lot of calls from numbers I do not recognize, I do not always answer, but a voice mail left with a return call number normally results in a return call. Today, I received a return call from the Chief Medical Director of MC and told her she would receive a copy of this document. Thank you for your attention to this matter.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hospital course 1/31 ? 2/20/21 1/31 in ED pt was at home when children noticed his lips were blue, ems arrived and found him to be 50% on RA, on Non-rebreather pt got to 78%, covid on 01/26   Shortness of Breath   61-year-old male presents with EMS for evaluation of shortness of breath hypoxia.  History is limited due to the patient's current clinical condition and so is primarily obtained from EMS.  EMS reports that he tested positive for COVID-19 5 days ago.  He began developing shortness of breath yesterday and his family called because his lips and fingers were blue today and he appeared short of breath.  On EMS arrival he had a room air saturation of less than 50% so he was placed on nonrebreather with improvement in his saturation to 70% and he was transported to the emergency department.  Patient does admit to shortness of breath.  He denies any chest pain.  He is noted to have a cast on his left ankle and said that he broke his left ankle on 23 December but has not had surgery.  He denies any new pain or swelling of the leg.  In the ED he was placed on 15L nasal cannula and NRB mask with improvement in SPO2 to low 90s. Additional work up revealed troponin of 1.35, lactic acid 5.8, and d-dimer 14.4.  He received dexamethasone and was placed on heparin gtt.   1/31 admitted to ICU Acute hypoxic respiratory failure due to COVID-19 vs heart failure vs PE.  CXR with bilateral hazy infiltrates more pronounced in the bases and left periphery and suspected multifocal pneumonia.   At risk for PE given LLE immobility in the setting of COVID-19 with significantly elevated d-dimer. RISK of CTA outweighs benefit given AKI and iodine allergy. Continue with empiric treatment with heparin gtt.   Admitted to ICU with SO2 in 60s-70s on 15L and NRB. Attempted 50L 95% FIO2 high flow and nasal cannula. Given lasix 40mg IV with good diuresis however SPO2 still remained low 80s with RR 40s and PO2 42 so the decision was made to intubate.  Oxygenation improved following intubation, with further improvement following recruitment maneuver and increase in PEEP. FIO2 weaned to 90% with SPO2 remaining in mid 90s. Will continue to wean FIO2 as able.  ARDS net protocol as much as possible. Consider prone ventilation and/or epoprostenol if unable to improve .  VAP Bundle: HOB >30 degrees; Oral care per nursing standard and on DVT/PPI prophylaxis Sedation: Target Richmond Agitation and Sedation Scale (RASS) of 0 to -2 with propofol and fentanyl. Check baseline TG levels.    COVID - 19: Convalescent plasma: Not indicated  Steroids: Dexamethasone 6 mg / day for 10 days Remdesivir: Not indicated d/t AKI   IL-6 inhibitor: Meets criteria for tocilizumab Systemic AC: Heparin gtt. No signs of bleeding (Platelets and Hb stable).  Antibiotics: Start 3 and 7 day course of azithromycin and ceftriaxone, respectively.  Elevated troponin  Suspect demand ischemia d/t hypoxia; EKG does not show any ischemic changes    AKI: Suspect d/t hypoxia in the setting of COVID infection. Urine output and electrolytes acceptable.  Closed fracture of left ankle Suffered fracture following a fall on ice in December. Cast was placed on 12/30 by SOS. He was due to be re-evaluated this week for possible cast removal.    Inhaled epoprostenol started  Considered for ECMO but not initiated due to not a candidate  Vasopressors required at times  Antihypertensive infusion required at times  severe hypoxia with position changes  switched from heparin drip to enoxaparin prophylaxis  2/20 discharge summary 61 y/o male admitted to Hospital on 1/31 with hypoxia.  He was diagnosed with COVID 19 5 days prior to admission, and had worsening respiratory status.  He was intubated after arrival, and was on ventilator for the entire intervening time, until he was extubated on 2/20 at the time of transition to Comfort measures only.    Prior to developing COVID 19, he had received his first dose of the Pfizer vaccine, as a member of the school system.  He had a fractured L ankle after a fall on 12/31/20, and had a cast in place at the time of admission.  He received Tocilizumab on 1/31, and underwent several cycles of prone positioning, beginning on 2/2.  He completed a course of Decadron, he received  Ceftriaxone and azithromycin beginning on admission, and completed a course of these.  Anticoagulation with enoxaparin was utilized due to coagulopathy associated with COVID 19.  Vasopressor support was required at times, as well as diuresis for fluid management.    He required high levels of sedation to maintain ventilator synchrony, and high levels of ventilator support with high oxygen levels throughout his stay.  Tracheostomy was being considered, but family decided that since he was not going to have good recovery, withdrawal of support, and allowing death was the appropriate choice for the patient and for them.   He was extubated at 2100 on 2/20/2021.   Death was pronounced at 2123 on 2/20/2021.  Children were at bedside.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Vaccine administration error: Technician administered Moderna COVID-19 vaccine to a patient using a prepackaged pre-assembled syringe.  At the time of immunization, the connection of the needle to the syringe was not tight and subsequently some vaccine escaped and ran down the patients arm. SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 20 minutes after the first shot, my mouth went numb.  The numbness moved across my entire face and moved down my throat.  I drove to the nearest pharmacy on my way home, and took one Benadryl.  I then drove to the ER.  It felt like my tongue  was swelling a little, but the Benadryl was controlling it.  The ER doctor said I had a good airway, and did not administer epinephrine.  He observed me for one hour and sent me home.  The left side of my face stayed numb for the rest of the night.  It was fine the next day.    I got the 2nd shot on Feb 26th.  I took 2 Benadryl right before in anticipation that this would happen again.  After the 2nd shot it took 40 minutes for my face to get partially numb.  The Benadryl seemed to keep it under control.  I got a 102 degree  fever the next day , on Feb 27th.  On Feb 28th I was severely nauseated, ached all over, had a bad headache, and was really "washed out".  This has continued (headache, nausea, and washed out feeling) most of the day  March 1, 2, and today (Mar, 3).  I am feeling a little better today, but it feels like I am recovering from the flu, where you have to sit down a lot.    I did not expect to feel this lousy for so long after the vaccine.
OTHER_MEDS: fish oil, magnesium taurate, MSM (joint supplement), vitamins A, B, C, and D3.  Multivitamins, CoQ10, GABA, ginko  biloba, mushroom complex supplement,  Allegra

Developed iritis form of uveitis shortly after getting vaccine. Felt feverish and very fatigued and sore the day after the vaccine (3/19/21), which was unexpected as I am generally healthy and do not recall having an adverse reaction to a vaccine before. Noticed prominent symptoms of iritis by around 2/22/21, but they may have been occurring earlier as I did not know what was happening to me. Symptoms started off as occasional aching of my right eye, but it eventually got inflamed and extra sensitive to light, and I experienced worse redness and aching/pain and photosensitivity by 2/26/21 when I scheduled an appointment with an optometrist. Pain/sensitivity was intermittent from 2/26/21 to  3/1/21, but redness remained. On 3/1/21, my optometrist tentatively diagnosed me with mild iritis and referred me to an opthalmologist. On 3/1/21, an opthalmologist diagnosed me with iritis/anterior uveitis, and I began a treatment of prednisolone acetate 1% drops. thought my development of iritis may have been related to me getting my first dose of the Covid-19 Moderna vaccine shortly before getting symptoms. Hoping to recover within  a few weeks. Have a follow-up appointment scheduled for 3/10/21.
LAB_DATA: No official tests have been conducted to date as far as I know, but I received a thorough eye exam from an optometrist on 3/1/21 and from an opthalmologist on 3/3/21.

Saturday morning around 10am, bruised feeling and tender at the back of the injected arm. Sore to touch that area and also sore to touch injection site.  Saturday Evening around 6pm pins and needles tingling sensation in both feet and also sharp stabbing pain on and off in left calf muscle.  Saturday night waking from sleep sweaty and disoriented. Sunday morning 10am light foggy feeling headache. Taken paracetamol with no change. Same symptoms continued on and off but were manageable at home. Monday evening dizziness during the day time and fstigue. Feeling of being drunk, everything in slow motion. Chest tightness began monday evening 8pm aprox (like my asthma symptoms) tickle in throat but no cough.  Woken up feeling cold but sweating. Tuesday morning mild headache again front of head. Chest tightness persisting but taken usual asthma medications. Tuesday evening 6pm Palpitations began. More of a hiding feeling than heart racing. Stronger than I have ever felt before and more frequent (6-8 times in 30 mins) Felt light headed again, hands and feet freezing cold and blue colour, body trembling, called NHS 111 advised A&E. Had blood tests, ECG and BP monitoring. ECG normal at the time but heart shows working harder than it should. Still waiting on blood results Weds (3/3/21)
LAB_DATA: Tuesday 2/3/21 ECG, blood tests and BP monitoring performed. Awaiting results.
HISTORY: Asthma  Eczema  Moderate high blood pressure

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Around 10:00-11:00 pm on 03/02/2021, I woke up with extreme soreness on left arm bicep (where injection was received and all over bicep). I kept waking up about every hour will chills and sweats as well as muscle and joint aches. From this time until approximately 7am, I used the restroom and urinated approximately 5 times. On an average night, I may use the restroom/urinate once at the most around 5-6AM.  This is usually only because the dog wakes me up to let her out at that time. At approximately 4am I took 40 mg (two 20mg pills) of DextroAmp-Amphet.  At 7am I attempted to shower for work. During my shower I couldn?t barely lift my arm to wash with out severe soreness. I also became very dizzy and nauseous. I had to get out and sit in front of the toilet because I thought I would vomit. Fortunately I did not. I then proceeded to crawl back into bed and call in to work (notifying them I was too sick to come in). I had extreme chills, muscle aches, and joint pain. I began to cry from hurting so bad. At approximately 7:45 I took 400mg of ibuprofen to help relieve symptoms. My body felt feverish (hot/clammy).  Around 8am I mustered up the strength to get dressed due to extreme chills. I then proceeded to eat a banana, peach yogurt, and a blueberry Benvita breakfast bar package with 4 wafers.  I then took a nap and have been laying in bed ever since until approximately 4:30 PM (with the exception of getup twice to urinate). My body hurt so bad, I barely moved. At approximately 4:30PM I got up to get orange juice and take 600 mg of ibuprofen.
OTHER_MEDS: Dextroamp-Amphet ER 40mg once daily in AM Buspirone HCL 10mg twice daily (AM/PM) Citalopram  20mg once daily in AM Ibuprofen 300mg at 7:30AM and 4:00PM on 3/3/21

4 days after getting the vaccine feeling extremely tired in the afternoon and like I was zoning out, and have had that feeling when my blood pressure has spiked before, but this was even worse--could barely keep my eyes open and felt weird, so measured my BP, and it initially read 190/151 which could not be right, but I know it was high.  I took it again a little while after, and it was down to 140/90, but usually is not that high when I've taken my full medication in the morning, which I did.  I then took my Spironoloactone.  BP was high for about an hour and then came down.  Don't know if it's related to the vaccine, but I haven't had it spike in quite a while, especially if I have taken my full amount of Losartan (which is 50mg), and while it may not have been 190, I know it was higher than it's ever spiked because I felt worse, and I can always feel when my BP goes up.  (There are days when my BP is too low to take the full pill, so I take half, but this day, I had taken the full pill.)  So, as I said, not sure if it's related to the vaccine or not, but was the worst I felt during a BP spike and lasted longer than ever did as well, but then came down without having to take any more medication except the Spironolactone, but it had come down a bit before that kicked in.

The first day, I had fatigue (tiredness) and  little bit of soreness in the arm of the injection. It was later on that night that I had to use my other arm to get my arm up to a cabinet to reach something. I went to bed early. The next day, still very fatigued, I still had the soreness in the muscle in the injection site arm. 10:30 am at work - it hit me almost like a flu - really quick that I started to feel very bad. Headache - light a migraine - it encompassed my whole head and started having low grade fever and severe nausea and abdominal pain and chills and severe body aches and bone achiness. Extreme fatigue. Side that I got the vaccine in, the glands in my neck and under my arm were swollen.  My fever was never only 100 - but 99.6 is where it usually ran and that was unusual for me to have a fever that high. I had had shingles about two years ago that affected my left side. I started to feel like my shingles was coming back. This felt like it was going to go from trunk all the way up to my neck (the shingles) - it didn't. I did have a few areas on my trunk area on that left side that did start - like a burning pain - no itchiness but they did go away. I had  flushing feeling - it was worse than a hot flash and different - it was like my body was extremely hot. My coworkers told me that I looked red as a bright red apple - and I wear makeup and had a face mask on. That continued for about 5 days - face, cheeks, especially below my chin, neck and my trunk - just really red. I have a photo of it. There was no pain to it - just hot flushing feeling. That was different from the shingles. The headache never went away - seven days - had trouble sleeping it was painful. It was almost like I had  flu. Like it might be going to my chest - Pulsometer - I check my pulse and my blood oxygen level - it went down to about 92 or 94% and I felt  a little short of breath and that lasted about two days.  I did not check my blood pressure.  The only other thing, like if you have the flu for ten days etc which is what my symptoms lasted- but the fatigue lasted another week past these severe intense reactions.

Patient remained in the vaccination chair for 5 minutes after injection and he reported feeling well and moved to the observation chair without any problems [~10ft].  After being the observation chair patient stood up and took 4-5 steps toward the wall and sat down on the floor.  The patient stated he felt dizzy and then became limp & slumped to the right side, eyes remained open with dilation of pupil fixed at 2mm with no blinking noted.  Patient's breathing pattern became shallow & snoring sounds noted.  Patient did not respond when spoken to nor did he respond to soft shaking of shoulders.  Patient began to demonstrate large jerky body movements similar to seizure activity.  The seizure like activity continued for 3-4 minutes before the patient was able to become aware of surroundings and answer orientation questions.  BP 120/72, HR 64, O2 sats 99%, RR 20.  Patient was diaphoretic, pale, shaking of hands and arms, restlessness of lower limbs with frequent repositioning/twitching of legs.  EMS arrived to find the patient regaining stability.  Patient reported to EMS that his is familiar with this type of response and declined to be taken to

Patient airway clear and breathing monitored. Patient regained consciousness, diaphoretic, oriented. Patient A&O x 4 after sternal rub. HR: 52, SPO2: 97% RA. Provided breath coaching, held patient in upright position, monitored breathing, had patient orally drink water. Manual B/P: 95/60, HR: 64. Patient became more coherent and stated prior to loss of consciousness he felt chest pain, denied any current chest pain, SOB, dizziness, headache, confusion, itching, rash, swelling.   Consulted with MD on site who advised EMS called and to monitor patient vitals. Patient declined EMS. Patient placed in wheelchair and taken to private room to lay supine and orally drink fluids. 15 minutes later supine vitals: B/P: 117/77 HR: 68, SPO2: 99% RA. Patient rested for additional 15 minutes, sat upright for 5 minutes. Vitals sitting: B/P 117/79, HR: 69, SPO2: 99% RA. Per MD, patient approved to return home but advised not to drive. Patient stated had not eaten or been drinking water and driven 2 hours prior to vaccination. Patient stated all symptoms resolved except feeling fatigued. Advised patient's wife to drive, to eat/drink prior to leaving, if develops chest pain, SOB, facial swelling, hives, loss of consciousness, lethargy, confusion to go to ER or call 911. Patient and wife verbalized understanding. Patient monitored for 1 hour after loss of consciousness.   Telephone call to patient 4 hours after vaccination. Patient stated "feeling much better," ate and drank water after leaving clinic, and resting. Patient denied SOB, chest pain, loss of consciousness, confusion, lethargy, HA, dizziness, lightheadedness. Patient advised to inform PCP of symptoms/reaction and discuss plan for when/if 2nd dose. Explained may have been vasovagal response. Patient stated several years ago having similar episode at ER when seeing blood, stated at vaccine clinic today, watched wife receive vaccine, then saw small drop of blood on his arm before loss of consciousness. Patient stated he will discuss with his PCP.

51 y/o female, no chronic health problems. 14 days following first COVID Pfizer vaccine, I felt unable to take a deep breath, on day 15 following the vaccine, I became short of breath,; on day 16 I was having mild chest pain with inspiration and shortness of breath;  day 17 following vaccination I became significantly short of breath, with moderate to severe chest pain with inspiration and tachycardia (heart rate in the 140's). I called my PCP who ordered an EKG, CXR, COVID swab, a metabolic panel,  a CBC, and a D-dimer. My D-dimer was elevated and he called me to go directly to the emergency department, which I did and had a CTA chest. I was diagnosed with multifocal pulmonary emboli in my right lung with a slight pleural effusion on my left lung. I had a duplex ultrasound of my legs which was negatve for DVT, and an echocardiogram which was within normal limits. I was finally diagnosed with acute unprovoked pulmonary embolism, given a Heparin bolus and started on a Heparin IV infusion. Ultimately, I transitioned to Eliquis PO and was discharged from the hospital within 24 hours.

On February 8th, 2021 patient came home early from work around noon due to not feeling well. She was feeling tired, slightly nauseous and very low energy. At about 4:50 PM that day, patient got up to walk to the pantry after eating some peanut butter toast. She suddenly stopped and shut her eyes and froze and then she began having a seizure (and she has never had a seizure before and seizures do not run in her family). After the shaking from the seizure ceased, her body tensed up and she fell flat backwards and she hit her head on the refrigerator. She then was going in and out of consciousness, she had a big laceration on her forehead and was bleeding rapidly. I, her daughter, witnessed this and then at 4:54 PM I called emergency services and paramedics arrived and took her to the hospital. Later that evening, the family was notified that the patient had bleeding in her brain, a concussion, a forehead laceration that received 15 stitches and a broken neck (C2 fracture). She was taken to the hospital that evening on February 8, 2021. Patuent experienced a second seizure while at the hospital during a CT scan. Patient later was able to come home February 11, 2021 in the afternoon. Patient now has to wear a neck brace for up to 12 weeks, cannot drive, cannot work for up to 12 weeks, and is still recovering cognitively from the concussion.
LAB_DATA: CT scan conducted on February 8, 2021 which determined a seizure occurred at home, also determined bleeding in the brain and a C2 fracture. Official injuries were declared: subarachnoid hemorrhage, traumatic brain injury, C2 fracture, seizure and forehead laceration
OTHER_MEDS: Buproprion XL (1 tablet 150 MG and 1 tablet 300 MG, both taken daily) and Venlafaxine ER 150 MG 1 tablet taken daily, fish oil, biotin, vitamin D, vitamin C, turmeric

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 8am Jan 20th (30 hrs after shot) I woke feeling extremely strong and powered up, very energized and liken the mental energy to feeling like I was on steroids. Went downstairs to kitchen to make a cup of tea and it was then I realized my pulse was going extremely fast (about 180bpm). I didn't think much of it or get nervous, but went to sit down and work at my computer, hoping it would go away, After about 20 minutes I realized it hadn't slowed down, so I went back to my bedroom to get dressed in the event I had to go to an urgent care or hospital. On the way up the stairs to my bedroom I realized I was getting a bit light-headed.  After about another 10 minutes I decided to lie down and called up a "calming meditation" app to see if that could lower my heart rate. I was able to get my heart rate down to about 125 after the10 minute meditation and it returned to normal shortly thereafter. The second episode was on February 11th. This time I was woken up out of my sleep at 4:45am by an extremely rapid heartbeat. Again, about 180bpm. This time I was a bit frightened. I walked around the house for about 15 minutes and when it didn't go down  I decided to go out for a walk. I did about a 30 minute walk , I had some tingling in my hands, but by the end of the walk my heart rate came down to about 100 and dropped back to normal shortly after.
LAB_DATA: EKG on 2/25/21, I do not have results yet
ALLERGIES: penicillin allergy from adolescence, but have taken it since them without incident. No other known allergies

On Monday night, Day 4, I woke at 11 p.m. with chills and shaking, temperature of 99.9 F. Went to the bathroom, urinated, took Tylenol and went back to bed. Woke again at 2:00 a.m, still chilled, and tried to stand up and my legs wouldn't hold me. I managed to lift myself to my feet and clutching furniture get to the bathroom, with complete loss of bladder control on the way. Took more Tyleonol, drank more water, put on clean pajamas but couldn't lift my knees to step into them, had to put them on the floor and pull them up. Went to sleep eventually. When I woke at about 5 a.m., all was completely normal. No fever, legs fine, usual bladder control.
LAB_DATA: I saw my PCP the next day (Tuesday) and was evaluated for possible stroke. There were no signs of muscle weakness, vision, etc. and he/she (2 docs in the room) prescribed an MRI of the brain which is scheduled for next week. He asked when was the last time I had had an a-fib event, and it was Friday night lasting several hours. I agree that some kind of stroke is a likely cause of these symptoms the the timing precisely coinciding with the Day 4 vaccine effects was weird.
OTHER_MEDS: Metoprolol. Xeralto, multivitamin, calcium, vitamin D

Our vaccine appointment (first dose) was on 2/28/21 at 1:45pm. We were sat at the station close to the window with my husband on one side and me to his left, near the front door. The prepped vaccine needles were in a blue tray on the table with new packaged needles in the tray as well. Most needles were covered except for one syringe with no needle cover.   The nurse came back from administering the vaccine to an elderly person in their car. She may have discarded something in the trash but I didn?t see her put anything on the table. She introduced herself and I was the first to be vaccinated. I watched her grab the one syringe with the needle exposed. An alarm rang in my head but I figured if something was wrong she would notice and it all happened quickly. She stuck the needle in my left arm and then declared that there was no vaccine in it. It had been empty. When my husband questioned her and asked if there would be any problems if I accidentally got 2 doses she said no, then she said she knew there was no vaccine because she ?didn?t have to push." When I asked if it was a used needle she said definitely not. She said she always discards the used needles. Her explanation for the incident was that she sometimes has to change out the needle (if it has been exposed) so she may have changed the needle and accidentally pushed the vaccine out. She also mentioned that sometimes the vaccine may leak out.  There was no explanation for why the needle would be uncovered.  We felt somewhat at ease but then got input from other RN?s and decided to call and report to the pharmacy the next day (3/1/21) to be safe since it was an uncovered needle. The pharmacist spoke with the nurse and she and the nurse, along with her husband (who preps some of the vaccines) called us back and explained what may have happened. They said they would follow Medical Center protocol and pay for any lab tests needed. They also said they would look at the medical form of the elderly person who was vaccinated before us to ask if they had any viral infections such as HIV and Hepatitis C. NOTE: If that needle had been previously used it is not certain that it had been used on that specific person.  On 3/2/21 the pharmacist's husband called and said they went over their procedures and had determined that there was no way the needle was previously used/dirty. This determination seemed to be based on taking the word of the nurse instead of trusting me that I had seen the exposed needle lying in the plastic bin of prepped needles. He had a doctor, who was apparently present at the pharmacy, ask about my past medical history, which didn't seem relevant. He told me that from then on I should talk to my doctor and if my doctor had questions the doctor could call them instead of me calling them.   When my husband returned home later on 3/2/21 we tried to get the pharmacist or her husband back on the phone but they did not return our call.     On 3/3/21 we called the pharmacy and spoke with the pharmacist via telephone and asked her if she had reported the incident. She said they had reported it to VAERS. She told us that she had worked with the nurse for years and she was 95% sure the needle had not been previously used. She said if she were in our position she would contact her doctor to see what needed to be done (preventative measures, etc.) and that we should do that, and then have our insurance take care of it rather than having them get involved in paying for any blood work.   We have no interest in making life difficult for anyone. We just want the proper health protocols followed to ensure my safety and to avoid having to shoulder the financial burden of ensuring that safety since the incident occurred at their location and under their care.   We spoke with our physician later on 3/3/21 and gave him the phone number to Pharmacy. We are waiting to hear what his recommendations are for us.

Within a few days was experiencing extreme pain in left leg, and difficulty walking. Pain ranged from lower left abdomen into leg down to calf. The pain , sharp, pins and needles, numbness got increasingly worse and began to experience atrophy in the left Quadriceps and Psoas. By the 15th I was unable to lift my leg off the floor in a lying down position and  was thought to be nerve  impingement /dysfunction.  For 2weeks following I was bed ridden not able to sit up , stand, move without bouts of excruciating pain. I could only lay on my right side. From Feb. 15th-Feb24th I had a CATScan,  Lumbar MRI, Pelvic MRI , 3 evaluations, and A dozen xrays with absolutely no findings or abnormalities in the spine, no tumors or hernias present, no issues with vertebrae or slip discs. Doctors were at a loss for diagnosis. I began to improve the 25th/26th of February gaining mobility and function back in my left leg. I have made almost a almost a complete recovery as of today , March 3 (yesterday March 2, I received my 2nd dose of Moderna. )

On the same day, he had hives on his upper lip. He took Benadryl (diphenhydramine) as treatment for hives that resolved the symptoms.
